What this fork started from
---------------------------
A lean copy of the parser library only — src/lib.rs, src/error.rs, src/raw/,
src/seq/, src/int/. Upstream's HTML viewer (src/main.rs, src/viewer/, the
`viewer` Cargo feature and its optional deps anyhow/clap/maud/open, the [[bin]]
target), upstream tests (they depend on an external `test-seqs` repo), and the
`assets/` directory were not carried over. Our own acceptance tests live in
crates/seq-validate-core/tests/; the Pulseq v1.5.1 spec is at
docs/refs/pulseq-spec-1.5.1.pdf.

Divergence from the fork point
------------------------------
Local changes made since 865a890 (this list will grow as the crate evolves):

  - src/interp/convert.rs + src/error.rs — `transform_grad` previously called
    `unimplemented!()` (a PANIC) when a rotation extension rotates gradient axes
    with different shapes/delays (e.g. stack-of-stars). Converted to a typed,
    recoverable error: new `InterpreterError::UnsupportedRotation { block_id }`;
    `transform_grad` now returns `Result` and `convert()` propagates it with `?`.
    A validator must not panic on input. The real fix (resample axes onto a
    common time grid) is planned for Step 5 (trajectory).

  - Pre-commit trim of orphaned vendor code (nothing in the workspace called
    these): removed `model::Gradient::delay()`, the unused `interp::Shape::new`
    (the `interp` ShapeLib builds `Shape` directly), and `Display for RfUse`.
    Added `type` aliases (`GradLookup`/`GradAxes` in interp/convert.rs,
    `ConvertedExts` in model/convert/mod.rs) to clear clippy `type_complexity`.
    `Shape::interpolate` (model + interp) was kept deliberately — unused today
    but needed for raster expansion in Step 5.

  - Narrowed to Pulseq 1.5 only (this validator targets 1.5+). Consolidated the
    four per-version parsers (`src/raw/pulseq_1_2..1_5.rs`) into a single
    `src/raw/parser.rs`, and `raw::parse_file` now rejects anything but 1.5 with
    `UnsupportedVersion`. Cascading removals of code that only existed to
    back-fill what older files omit:
      * `raw::Delay` + `[DELAYS]` parsing + `Section::Delays` +
        `SectionType::Delays` (Delay events were removed in 1.4);
      * `raw::BlockDuration` enum → `Block.dur: u32` (1.4+ blocks store an
        explicit duration, never a delay-id);
      * `raw::Gradient.first/last` → non-optional `f64` (always present in 1.5),
        and the whole pre-1.5 boundary back-fill: `compute_grad_boundaries`,
        `raw_shape_duration_ticks`, `helpers::extrapolate_grad_boundaries`;
      * the pre-1.4 branch + `TimeRaster::default()` (rasters are mandatory);
        `EventType::Delay` (now unreachable).
    Output is unchanged for 1.5 files: the old boundary walker simply returned
    each gradient's explicit `first`/`last`, which the simplified path now reads
    directly. Verified by the existing fixture + snapshot tests.

  - src/interp/mod.rs — added `Sequence::block_starts()` and
    `Sequence::duration()` to the interpreted layer. Blocks play back to back,
    so absolute block start times and total duration are a pure function of the
    interpreted blocks ("what the scanner plays"). They previously lived in
    seq-validate-core's IR facade; moved down here so every `interp` consumer
    shares one definition and the facade is left holding only file provenance
    (version/definitions).

  - Renamed two layer modules for clarity, since the originals collided with
    common identifiers — including ones used *inside this very crate*:
    `seq` → `model` (collided with the `.seq` extension and winnow's `seq!`
    record macro) and `int` → `interp` (collided with the integer-parsing
    combinator `int`, used ~30× in src/raw/parser.rs). `raw` was left as-is.
    Path references in the earlier entries above were updated to the new names.
    NOTE: the "What this fork started from" and "Pulling later upstream"
    sections still say `seq`/`int` deliberately — those describe *upstream's*
    layout at the fork point, which is what you would diff against.

Pulling later upstream improvements (optional)
----------------------------------------------
We don't track upstream, but if a future upstream fix is worth adopting, diff
upstream's src/{raw,seq,int,error.rs,lib.rs} at the newer commit against ours and
cherry-pick by hand. There is no expectation of staying in sync.
